inthedarkplace wrote:

&gt;Is anybody really interested in URIs that&#39;s you can&#39;t dereference? And
&gt;also, I&#39;d like to point out that you can dereference URNs... various
&gt;protocols do exist and are in use to do that. 
&gt;
Well, many namespace names are URIs.  While there is some (much) debate, 
I think many don&#39;t expect to dereference a namespace name.

There seems to be a desire on some people&#39;s part to be able to say that 
if a URI uses a scheme that is dereferencable, the you must be able to 
dereference the URI.  Or conversely, if I have a name that I don&#39;t want 
to be dereferenced, then I shouldn&#39;t use a URI with a dereferencable 
scheme.  Personally, I don&#39;t understand the problem - a name is a name. 
 Some will dereference, other will not.

&gt;
&gt;I know the problem I&#39;m trying to solve is this: given a set of of HTTP
&gt;resources, how can orthogonal &#39;metadata&#39; that real clients don&#39;t care
&gt;about be associated with the resources in a clean, simple manner that
&gt;doesn&#39;t involve radical alterations to the pre-existing web.
&gt;  
&gt;
This is another one I don&#39;t really understand (the general case, not 
your specific problem).  How do you determine what is metadata and what 
is data?  (One person&#39;s metadata is another&#39;s data).  Why isnt a chunk 
of metadata for a resource just another resource?  And does it really 
make sense to only allow the owner of a resource to provide metadata for 
that resource.  To me, the question of how do I find metadata for a 
resource sounds a lot like &#39;how do i find out what resources point to 
this resource?&#39;

--Chuck

